{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e717949b-33d4-4987-815d-d327aa0312f0","content":"Two things change with xUnit v3 + MTP:\n\n**1. Filter syntax** — MTP doesn't use VSTest's `&` / `~` syntax. It uses `--filter` with different operators:\n\n| VSTest | MTP |\n|---|---|\n| `~` (contains) | `~=` |\n| `&` (and) | `&` (same) |\n| `FullyQualifiedName` | `FullyQualifiedName` (same) |\n| `Category` | ❌ not recognized |\n\n**2. `Category` → trait syntax** — MTP doesn't map `Category` automatically. For xUnit traits you must use the format `Category=Smoke` as a single trait expression.\n\n### New CI command\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~=IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke\"\n```\n\nThe key change is `~` → `~=` (MTP's \"contains\" operator). The `Category=Smoke` part works because MTP + xUnit v3 recognizes xUnit `[Trait(\"Category\", \"Smoke\")]` when expressed this way.\n\nIf you ever use a custom trait name (e.g., `[Trait(\"Priority\", \"High\")]`), the filter would be `Priority=High`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2a43d95e-4d7f-4da8-83c0-37305414f5a6","outputTokens":306,"requestId":"0839:5FAF2:7E31DA4:8C6C7B2:69EABF58"},"id":"13f5d138-cc95-4703-aa2b-bff190e7ac87","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:54:55.860Z","parentId":"2567f835-6665-4a6a-b049-7ca923bf61f9"}
